==English==

===Etymology===
Old French ''abatement'', French ''abattement''.

===Noun===
'''abatement'''

#The act of [[abating]], or the state of being [[abate]]d; a [[lessening]], [[diminution]], or reduction; removal or putting an end to; as, the '''abatement''' of a [[nuisance]] is the [[suppression]] [[thereof]].
#The amount abated; that which is taken away by way of reduction; [[deduction]]; [[decrease]]; a [[rebate]] or [[discount]] allowed.
#''(Heraldry):'' A mark of [[dishonor]] on an [[escutcheon]].
#''(Law):'' The [[entry]] of a [[stranger]], without right, into a [[freehold]] after the death of the last [[possessor]], before the heir or [[devisee]]. - [[Blackstone]]

===Derived expressions===
*'''Defense in abatement''', '''Plea in abatement''', ''(Law):'', plea to the effect that from some formal defect (e.g. [[misnomer]], want of jurisdiction) the proceedings should be abated.

